ongestion, (b) the environment and (c) road safety through a modal shift to motorcycles and scooters.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker","277180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138879","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-23","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are responsible for the collection and collation of audiology data to enable them to manage regional needs. NHS England has no plans to mandate CCGs to collect or publish their data in a comparable form.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-07-23T16:03:42.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138879/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138879/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138879/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-15","Audiology and Hearing Aids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer on 12 June 2019 to Question 260081, whether his Department will require Clinical Commissioning Groups to collect and publish data in a comparable form on (a) the amount spent on audiology services, (b) the number of hearing aids fitted and (c) outcomes of hearing aid fittings.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","277193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138880","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-22","<p>​We are aware of the BBC Africa Eye investigation which alleges that senior Sudanese military rulers ordered the killing of protestors on 3 June. In his statement of 3 June, the Foreign Secretary condemned the attack on protestors by Sudanese security forces and said that the Transitional Military Council (TMC) bore full responsibility for these events. The UK has been clear, at both ministerial and official levels, that there must be justice and accountability for atrocities committed both by the former regime and more recently. On 23 June, the UK Envoy to Sudan and South Sudan delivered this message directly to the Sudanese authorities. The UK has also made public statements in multilateral fora such as the EU Foreign Affairs Council (17 June) and the UN Human Rights Council (9 July). We note the agreement between the TMC and Forces of Freedom and Change to conduct a transparent and independent investigation into the violence committed against peaceful protestors on 3 June.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-07-22T14:50:12.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138880/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138880/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138880/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-15","Sudan: Demonstrations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Sudanese counterpart on the reports of the killing of peaceful protesters in Sudan in June.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","277196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138881","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-22","<p>​We are aware of the BBC Africa Eye investigation which alleges that senior Sudanese military rulers ordered the killing of protestors on 3 June. In his statement of 3 June, the Foreign Secretary condemned the attack on protestors by Sudanese security forces and said that the Transitional Military Council (TMC) bore full responsibility for these events. The UK has been clear, at both ministerial and official levels, that there must be justice and accountability for atrocities committed both by the former regime and more recently. On 23 June, the UK Envoy to Sudan and South Sudan delivered this message directly to the Sudanese authorities. The UK has also made public statements in multilateral fora such as the EU Foreign Affairs Council (17 June) and the UN Human Rights Council (9 July). We note the agreement between the TMC and Forces of Freedom and Change to conduct a transparent and independent investigation into the violence committed against peaceful protestors on 3 June.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-07-22T14:52:55.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138881/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138881/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138881/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-15","Sudan: Demonstrations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the accuracy of the findings of the BBC Africa Eye investigation that the killing of protesters in Sudan on 3 June was ordered by that country’s senior military rulers.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","277197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138882","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-22","<p>I am deeply concerned by the security situation in Mali, particularly central Mali, which has experienced a recent increase in violence. As I have previously stated, it is essential that the perpetrators are brought to justice, that the cycle of violence is ended, and that impunity is tackled.</p><p>As part of the Government's new strategic approach to Africa, we are increasing our engagement with and support to the Sahel region. Along with increasing our presence in Mali and Mauritania, we will be opening new embassies in Niger and Chad, and have created a new cross-Government Joint Sahel Department that combines our defence, development, and diplomatic expertise so that we embody a truly comprehensive approach to supporting the region to tackle its complex challenges.</p><p>The Defence Secretary visited Mali this month and announced that UK Armed Forces will deploy to Mali in 2020 in support of the UN Peacekeeping Operation; United Nations Multidimensional Integrated Stabilization Mission in Mali (MINUSMA), to which the UK is the sixth largest funder. The existing commitment of three UK Chinooks and accompanying personnel has been extended for six months.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-07-22T14:51:40.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138882/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138882/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138882/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-15","Mali: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the security situation in Mali.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","277198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138883","Department for International Development","false","2019-07-19","<p>The UK is deeply concerned by the increasing levels of violence in Mali. The number of displaced people across Mali has more than tripled in the past year. Through the Sahel Humanitarian Emergency Response Programme (SHERP), the UK is providing Mali with £11.1m of humanitarian aid this year, providing emergency food aid, emergency nutrition activities, and protection assistance to conflict-affected and displaced people across Mali.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-07-19T12:14:24.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138883/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138883/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138883/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-07-15","Mali: Internally Displaced People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support his Department provides to Mali to tackle the increasing number of internally displaced persons.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","277199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138884","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-22","<p>​I refer the Honourable Member to the answers of 11 June 2019 (PQ 259251) and 17 June (PQ 263167).</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-07-22T10:32:40.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138884/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138884/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138884/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-15","Kashmir: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the security situation in Kashmir.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","277200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138885","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-22","<p>Figures on the total number of electric vehicle chargepoints are unavailable. Members of the public and businesses are able to install chargepoints without government support, and information on these are not routinely collected. Chargepoints that do receive government funding can be decommissioned or removed without notifying Government. The charging point platform Zap-map reports that, as at July 16<sup>th</sup>, there are 19,939 publicly available connectors in England, with the numbers in each region as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Region</p></td><td><p>Number of chargepoint connectors</p></td><td><p>Percentage within England</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>1,299</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>1,618</p></td><td><p>8%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Greater London</p></td><td><p>6,417</p></td><td><p>32%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>1,045</p></td><td><p>5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>1,807</p></td><td><p>9%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>3,239</p></td><td><p>16%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>1,903</p></td><td><p>10%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>1,388</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and the Humber</p></td><td><p>1,223</p></td><td><p>6%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2019-07-22T16:00:56.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138885/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138885/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138885/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-15","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many charging points for electric vehicles there are in England; and how many of those are located in each region.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","277244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138886","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-23","<p>The Government has had a number of discussions with representatives of the oil sector about the provision of electric vehicle charge points at service stations and petrol forecourts. We are encouraging the private sector to invest in and operate a self-sustaining public network supported by the right policy framework. Only last week, the Prime Minister and the Secretary of State for Transport met with automotive industry leaders, where there was a discussion about having the right charging infrastructure in place and a number of new commitments about charging were made to make electric vehicles more convenient than ever to own. The Government’s view is that the market is often better placed to identify the right locations for chargepoints and it is essential that viable commercial models are in place to ensure continued maintenance and improvements to the network. As evidence of this, BP Chargemaster, the UK’s largest electric car charge point provider, announced last month that it will install 400 points capable of ultra-fast 150kW charging by 2021 – including 100 at 50 sites by the end of 2019.</p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2019-07-23T12:03:02.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138886/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138886/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138886/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-15","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with the oil sector on introducing charging points for electric vehicles at  (a) service stations and (b) petrol forecourts.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","277245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138887","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-23","<p>Our mission is to put the UK at the forefront of the design, manufacture and uptake of zero emission vehicles. We are investing more than £1.5bn between 2015 and 2021 to support this. The plug-in car grant continues to support the purchase of the cleanest vehicles and will remain in place until at least 2020. Our Road to Zero Strategy confirmed that consumer incentives in some form will continue to play a role beyond 2020.</p><p> </p><p>The government recently announced company car tax rates out to 2022-23. To accelerate the shift to zero emission cars, all zero emission models will pay no company car tax in 2020-21, 1% in 2021-22 before returning to the planned 2% rate in 2022-23 – a significant tax saving for employees and employers.</p><p> </p><p>Alongside other measures in the government’s Road to Zero strategy, including support schemes for the installation of charge points, the UK government’s support package adds up to one of the most comprehensive worldwide. As part of the upcoming spending review, government will be setting out funding and other measures for future years.</p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2019-07-23T12:24:30.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138887/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138887/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138887/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-15","Electric Vehicles: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to replace the plug-in car grant to encourage the manufacture and sale of low emission vehicles.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","277246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138888","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-19","<p>NHS England commissions specialised services for people living with sickle cell disease. These services are part of the specialised haemoglobinopathy services commissioned by NHS England across the country. NHS England spends over £60 million on sickle cell disease within these services annually - £60.4 million in 2017/18. Information about the services provided by individual clinical commissioning groups or other public bodies is not collected or held centrally.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-07-19T09:46:21.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138888/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138888/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138888/answer","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138888/answer/previousversion/129855","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-15","Sickle Cell Diseases: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 23 May 2019 to Question 256313 on Sickle Cell Diseases, which services (a) NHS England, (b) clinical commissioning groups and (c) other public bodies commission for people with sickle cell disease; and what the per capita annual cost is of providing each of those services.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","277137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138889","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-19","<p>NHS England does not commission separate services for sickle cell patients with stroke, chronic kidney disease, end-stage renal disease or pulmonary hypertension and so cannot provide annual per capita costs. These services are commissioned on behalf of all patients that require them, which would include people living with sickle cell disease.</p><p>NHS England has recently undertaken a review of haemoglobinopathy services to ensure that patients living with conditions such as sickle cell disease are able to access the high-quality services they need for their condition across the country. NHS England is now commissioning a networked-based model of care for specialised haemoglobinopathy services which will included specialist haemoglobinopathy teams across the country, regional haemoglobinopathy coordination centres and a National Haemoglobinopathy Panel. The new model will enable advice to be provided to local clinicians on the management of patients with sickle cell disease 24 hours a day, seven days a week. Haemoglobinopathy coordination centres will organise and run networks for sickle cell disease, providing leadership and education for local services.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-07-19T09:45:39.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138889/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138889/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138889/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-15","Sickle Cell Diseases: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 23 May 2019 to Question 256313, which  services (a) NHS England, (b) clinical commissioning groups and (c) other public bodies commission for sickle cell disease patients with (i) stroke, (ii) chronic kidney disease, (iii) end-stage renal disease and (iv) pulmonary hypertension; and what the annual per capita cost is of providing each of those services.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","277138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138890","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-07-18","<p>The information requested on the number of people with Sickle Cell Disease in receipt of Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) and Universal Credit (UC) and the cost to the public purse of providing support for claimants with Sickle Cell Disease for ESA and UC is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Information on health conditions of ESA claimants is only available by high level medical conditions, including Diseases of the Blood and Blood forming organs and certain diseases involving the immune mechanism, is published on Stat-Xplore.</p><p> </p><p>The latest data on PIP claims in payment can be which can be broken down by month from April 2013 to April 2019 and by disability which includes Sickle Cell Anaemia can be found on Stat-Xplore too: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p>Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p><p> </p><p>The latest data on the PIP expenditure broken down by disability subgroup including Haemolytic disease, of which Sickle Cell Disease is one disease is in this category is published and can be found at: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/741592/pip-expenditure-by-medical-condition-2017-18.ods" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/741592/pip-expenditure-by-medical-condition-2017-18.ods</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-07-18T13:36:17.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138890/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138890/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138890/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-07-15","Social Security Benefits: Sickle Cell Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people with sickle cell disease were in receipt of (a) personal independence payments and (b) employment support allowance or their universal credit equivalents in the most recent period for which data are available; and what the annual cost to the public purse of providing that support in each of those groups is.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","277139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138891","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-07-18","<p>With regard to Personal Independence Payment (PIP), Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) and Universal Credit (UC), the information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>With regards to PIP, we only record the main disabling condition for a claimant on analytical datasets and so cannot answer questions on combinations of conditions without incurring disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Information on health conditions of ESA claimants is only available by high level medical conditions, including Diseases of the Blood and Blood forming organs and certain diseases involving the immune mechanism, is published here:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-07-18T13:25:29.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138891/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138891/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138891/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-07-15","Social Security Benefits: Sickle Cell Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in receipt of (a) personal independence payment and (b) employment support allowance and their universal credit equivalents have sickle cell disease with (i) stroke,(ii) sickle chronic kidney disease, (iii) end-stage renal disease and (iv) pulmonary hypertension in the most recent period for which figures are available; and what the annual cost to the public purse of providing that support in each of those groups is.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","277140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138892","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-07-18","<p>As of November 2018, around 860,000 carers received Carer’s Allowance. The Department is forecast to spend around £3bn in 2019/20 supporting these carers to provide support to people with a range of conditions, disabilities and illnesses.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested on the number of Carer’s Allowance claimants caring for people with multiple specific conditions is not available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-07-18T14:07:48.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138892/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138892/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138892/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-07-15","Carer's Allowance: Sickle Cell Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many carers of people with (a) sickle cell disease and (b) sickle cell disease and (i) stroke, (ii) chronic kidney disease, (iii) end-stage renal disease and (iv) pulmonary hypertension received carer’s allowance in the most recent period for which figures are available; and what the annual cost to the public purse of providing that support in each of those groups is.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","277141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138893","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-07-18","<p>The Government has over 300 work streams looking at specific no deal plans across a range of sectors and these are well advanced. There is still some work to be done but departments are making sensible decisions about prioritisation.</p><p>The underlying detail for each workstream, including any assessment of those programmes, is exceptionally sensitive. If workstreams - or the underlying data - were made public, both our negotiating position and our ability to manage delivery across the programme would be significantly damaged.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","James Cleverly","277296","2019-07-18T16:58:20.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138893/answer","Biography information for James Cleverly","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138893/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138893/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-07-15","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to the oral evidence from the Permanent Secretary of the Department for Exiting the European Union to the Committee on Exiting the European Union of 4 September 2018, if he will list the 300 cross-government workstreams on the UK leaving the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Neil O'Brien","Harborough","Neil O'Brien","277295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138894","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-07-23","<p>Programme funding was allocated to projects that will best help bring threatened species back from the brink, rather than on a regional basis. Projects are delivered across multiple locations so we are unable to give detailed geographical breakdowns. However, as part of the Ancients of the Future project, funding is being used in Lanhydrock, North Cornwall, and nearby Fowey Valley to survey, provide advice to land managers, and upskill local tree surgeons in techniques to manage ancient trees and woodlands providing habitat for bats and other wildlife. Another project aims to improve the prospects for the vulnerable Lesser Butterfly Orchid by providing advice to land managers in Greena Moor and nearby in Dunsdon National Nature Reserve.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-07-23T16:36:11.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138894/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138894/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138894/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-07-15","Nature Conservation: North Cornwall","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much of the £7.7 million funding for the Back from the Brink programme is accessible to North Cornwall.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","277227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138895","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-22","<p>The current Great Western franchise agreement expires at 01.59am on 1 April 2020, having been extended to the fullest extent possible under its terms. In November 2017 the Secretary of State announced his intention to negotiate a new franchise agreement with the incumbent operator and discussions with FirstGroup are already under way.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-07-22T16:09:12.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138895/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138895/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138895/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-15","Great Western Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to commence negotiations with the First Group on the terms of an extension to the Great Western franchise after March 2020.","false","Biography information for George Eustice","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","277158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138896","Cabinet Office","false","2019-07-18","<p>Ministerial approval has been set at £750 per day as a control mechanism to consistently achieve value for money, provide greater transparency and to ensure that all other resourcing options have been considered.</p>","Torbay","Kevin Foster",,"2019-07-18T09:22:37.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138896/answer","Biography information for Kevin Foster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138896/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138896/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-07-15","Temporary Employment: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, for what reasons the rate of pay which requires approval for temporary staff was set at £750 per day in his Departments announcement of 4 July.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","277113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138897","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-07-18","<p>The Government has over 300 work streams looking at specific no deal plans across a range of sectors and these are well advanced. There is still some work to be done but departments are making sensible decisions about prioritisation.</p><p>The underlying detail for each workstream, including any assessment of those programmes, is exceptionally sensitive. If workstreams - or the underlying data - were made public, both our negotiating position and our ability to manage delivery across the programme would be significantly damaged.</p><p> </p>","Braintree","James Cleverly","277295","2019-07-18T16:58:20.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138897/answer","Biography information for James Cleverly","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138897/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138897/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-07-15","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to the oral evidence from the Permanent Secretary of the Department for Exiting the European Union to the Committee on Exiting the European Union of 4 September 2018, at the point where they were last assessed, how many cross-departmental workstreams on the UK leaving the EU without a deal were rated as (a) red, (b) red/amber, (c) amber, (d) amber/green and (e) green.","false","Biography information for Neil O'Brien","Harborough","Neil O'Brien","277296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138898","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-22","<p>The Department published the response to its consultation on the future of the Great Western franchise on 28 August 2018: (https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/736146/great-western-rail-franchise-stakeholder-briefing-document.pdf). This shows ten areas of response from consultees about catering.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-07-22T16:11:54.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138898/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138898/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138898/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-15","Great Western Railway: Catering","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what representations he has received on the standard of catering services on the new Class 800 trains operated by First Group under the Great Western franchise.","false","Biography information for George Eustice","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","277159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138899","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-22","<p>The Department published the response to its consultation on the future of the Great Western franchise on 28 August 2018: (https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/736146/great-western-rail-franchise-stakeholder-briefing-document.pdf). This shows ten areas of response from consultees about catering, including comments about both trolley services and buffet cars</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-07-22T16:16:11.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138899/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138899/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138899/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-15","Great Western Railway: Catering","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect on passengers of the decision by the First Group to discontinue its buffet car facilities and replace them with a more limited trolley service.","false","Biography information for George Eustice","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","277160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138900","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-22","<p>The Department published the response to its consultation on the future of the Great Western franchise on 28 August 2018: (https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/736146/great-western-rail-franchise-stakeholder-briefing-document.pdf). Decisions on policy on the specification of the next Great Western franchise are informed by this consultation, which did not show strong demand for full buffet car catering facilities.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-07-22T16:14:07.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138900/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138900/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138900/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-15","Great Western Railway: Catering","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to make it a condition of any future extension of the Great Western franchise that an operator must provide full buffet car catering facilities.","false","Biography information for George Eustice","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","277161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138901","Department for Education","false","2019-07-18","<p>The Department publishes the income and expenditure, including revenue balances, annually for local authority maintained schools and for academies.</p><p>The Department published data for local authority maintained schools’ Consistent Financial Reporting (CFR) for the years 2013-14 to 2017-18 at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-local-authority-school-finance-data#local-authority-and-school-finance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-local-authority-school-finance-data#local-authority-and-school-finance</a>.</p><p>The Department published data for academy schools’ Academies’ Accounting Returns (AAR) for 2016/17, when revenue reserve was first collected at school level, and 2017/18 at: <a href="https://schools-financial-benchmarking.service.gov.uk/Help/DataSources" target="_blank">https://schools-financial-benchmarking.service.gov.uk/Help/DataSources</a>.</p><p>The attached tables give the requested breakdown. Information for years prior to those provided are not available. The figures for academies are as reported for the individual schools and do not include any surpluses or deficits at trust level for those in multi academy trusts.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-07-18T15:55:06.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138901/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138901/answer","277297_school_deficits_table.pdf","277297_PDF","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138901/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-15","Primary Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of primary schools which had (a) fewer than 100, (b) 101 to 200, (c) 201 to 300, (d) 301 to 400, (e) 401 to 600 and (f) 601 or more pupils, were in deficit in each of the five most recent years for which data are available.","false","Biography information for Neil O'Brien","Harborough","Neil O'Brien","277297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138902","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-23","<p>NHS Digital publishes hospital and community health services workforce statistics for National Health Service trusts and clinical commissioning groups in England. However, the information held by NHS Digital does not capture sufficient level of detail to identify those working in cancer care in Cornwall.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-07-23T16:35:45.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138902/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138902/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138902/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-15","Cancer: Cornwall","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many (a) doctors and (b) nurses are employed on a full-time basis for cancer care in Cornwall.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","277228"
