made such complaints.","false","Biography information for Lord Rogan",,"Lord Rogan","HL17174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139090","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-07-23","<p>The Northern Ireland Office takes its responsibilities under Fair Employment legislation very seriously and seeks to ensure a good and harmonious working environment for all staff; the requirements of which are set out in the 1989 Fair Employment Code of Practice.</p><p> </p><p>In line with the Equality Commission of Northern Ireland’s Guide, Promoting a Good and Harmonious Working Environment, the Northern Ireland Office is sensitive to the display of “posters, pictures, portraits or other displays that are more closely associated with one or other of the communities” and will consider any concerns raised by employees. I can confirm that the department takes steps to ensure no such images are displayed in Stormont House</p><p> </p><p>Information on employees’ personal data is sensitive, in order to comply with DPA requirements, and so I am unable to comment further. In line with the rest of the Civil Service, our staff need to be able to raise concerns in a confidential manner and without fear of repercussions.</p><p> </p><p>In relation to the Northern Ireland Assembly, I would refer the noble Lord to the Clerk/ Chief Executive of the Northern Ireland Assembly.</p>",,"Lord Duncan of Springbank","HL17173 ; HL17174","2019-07-23T15:47:57.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139090/answer","Biography information for Lord Duncan of Springbank","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139090/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139090/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-07-15","Northern Ireland Assembly and Northern Ireland Office: Art Works","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether any Northern Irish civil servants received compensation for offence caused by portraits of the Royal Family; if so, how many; and in each case, how much compensation was awarded.","false","Biography information for Lord Rogan",,"Lord Rogan","HL17175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139091","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-07-24","<p>The 2019 Judicial Diversity Statistics provide data on the diversity of the judiciary, as of 1 April 2019. Disability information is currently collected on a non-mandatory basis by self-declaration. Disability information of judicial office holders is not presented as part of the statistics as, for those who do not declare a disability, it is not currently possible to differentiate between those without a disability and those who chose not to respond to the disability question.</p><p> </p><p>From 2019/2020, Judicial Office are changing the way they collect diversity information to help resolve this issue. This will allow judges to access all of their diversity information on a regular basis to ensure it is up to date and accurate. Judicial Office will begin to collect more robust disability information, alongside other diversity information, with the aim of including it in the published statistics, subject to appropriate declaration rates.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL17177","2019-07-24T11:51:27.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139091/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139091/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139091/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-07-15","Judiciary: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, following the publication by the Courts and Tribunals Judiciary of the Judicial Diversity Statistics 2019 on 11 July, what consideration they have given to reporting statistics on disability in the judiciary.","false","Biography information for Lord Shinkwin",,"Lord Shinkwin","HL17176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139092","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-07-24","<p>The 2019 Judicial Diversity Statistics provide data on the diversity of the judiciary, as of 1 April 2019. Disability information is currently collected on a non-mandatory basis by self-declaration. Disability information of judicial office holders is not presented as part of the statistics as, for those who do not declare a disability, it is not currently possible to differentiate between those without a disability and those who chose not to respond to the disability question.</p><p> </p><p>From 2019/2020, Judicial Office are changing the way they collect diversity information to help resolve this issue. This will allow judges to access all of their diversity information on a regular basis to ensure it is up to date and accurate. Judicial Office will begin to collect more robust disability information, alongside other diversity information, with the aim of including it in the published statistics, subject to appropriate declaration rates.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL17176","2019-07-24T11:51:27.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139092/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139092/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139092/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-07-15","Judiciary: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, following the publication by the Courts and Tribunals Judiciary of the Judicial Diversity Statistics 2019 on 11 July, on what grounds it was decided not to report on the prevalence of disability among judicial office-holders.","false","Biography information for Lord Shinkwin",,"Lord Shinkwin","HL17177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139093","Department for Education","false","2019-07-23","<p>The department requires a high level of accountability and transparency of trusts and has robust processes in place for monitoring their performance. This includes collecting and publishing a wide range of information, such as tables setting out measures of educational performance; financial benchmarking tables; and letters to academy trusts about poor or inadequate performance or weaknesses in safeguarding, governance and/or financial management. This goes beyond the information that the department publishes about local authorities.</p><p>Ofsted plays a vital role in holding trusts to account by providing independent judgements on the educational performance of schools within a trust and through its process of summary evaluations. Ofsted has so far published 6 summary evaluations of academy trusts since their introduction in December 2018.</p><p>The department will continue to make information about trusts more visible. As we do this, we will ensure that accountability is robust, transparent and proportionate for all schools.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2019-07-23T11:10:03.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139093/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139093/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139093/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-15","Academies: Inspections","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the recommendations of the Ofsted report, Multi-academy trusts: benefits, challenges and functions, published on 15 July, and in particular the recommendation that Ofsted be empowered to inspect both multi-academy trusts and individual schools in order to strengthen their accountability.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL17178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139094","Leader of the House of Lords","false","2019-07-23","<p>As the Prime Minister has said before, everyone working in Parliament deserves to be treated with dignity and respect. This inquiry has brought to light behaviour which is unacceptable, and it is incumbent on the House of Lords to take swift action. It is important that the House now carefully considers the concerns raised in this important report, and responds to its recommendations.</p><p>It is primarily for Parliament, rather than Government, to consider how best to respond to Naomi Ellenbogen QC’s recommendations. The House of Lords Commission met on Wednesday 17 July in order to plan its response to the recommendations. Every member of the Commission committed to complete the Valuing Everyone training course, and the leaders of the political groupings committed their front bench to do the same. The Commission agreed the establishment of a Steering Group of staff, members and others to embark on the process of moving forward with Naomi Ellenbogen QC’s recommendations, and the new Conduct Committee will examine those which relate to the Code of Conduct.</p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park",,"2019-07-23T14:16:47.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139094/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139094/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139094/answer",,,,,"92",,"Leader of the House of Lords","2019-07-15","Bullying and Harassment in the House of Lords Independent Inquiry","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the report by Naomi Ellenbogen QC An Independent Inquiry into bullying and harassment in the House of Lords, published on 11 July.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL17179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139095","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-07-23","<p>HM Government has no plans to amend current legislation on digital content. However, the Government has committed to retaining strong protections for consumers post Brexit.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2019-07-23T13:16:27.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139095/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139095/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139095/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-07-15","Digital Technology: Sales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to reform the Consumer Rights Act 2015 rules for digital content purchased post-Brexit to include a 28-day refund rule.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL17180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139096","Department for International Trade","false","2019-07-23","<p>The number of negotiators required is dependent on how many trade agreements are ongoing at any given time and will involve teams of differing sizes, with expertise relevant to the specific chapters of sectors. The Department for International Trade has reviewed its resource requirements and continue to do so to ensure that it is sufficiently staffed. Since the Department was created its Trade Policy Group (TPG) has grown to approximately 700 people at the end of June 2019, bringing together trade policy, country specialists and experts on trade policy issues.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2019-07-23T17:00:16.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139096/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139096/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139096/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-07-15","Trade Agreements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of reports of a shortage of experienced UK trade negotiators during the Brexit process.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL17181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139097","Home Office","false","2019-07-23","<p>The Government’s position remains that leaving with a deal, which includes ambitious internal security arrangements, is in the UK’s best interests.</p><p><br>We continue to work closely with operational partners to maintain readiness for a range of possible exit scenarios in October, including no deal. This includes taking into account risks associated with these scenarios.</p><p><br>The Home Office has therefore been working with operational partners to put in place contingency arrangements for a no deal scenario.</p><p><br>In a deal scenario, the UK would enter an implementation period during which we’d continue to use all the EU security tools we use now.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-07-23T15:10:15.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139097/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139097/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139097/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-15","Organised Crime","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of reports that there may be a rise in cross-border organised crime after Brexit; and if so, what steps they are taking to address this.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL17182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139098","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-31","<p>We are aware of the case of Hotheifa Bader Khalifa. While we have not raised the matter with our Israeli counterparts, we remain concerned about Israel’s use of administrative detention which, according to international law, should only be used when security makes this absolutely necessary rather than as routine practice, and as a preventative rather than punitive measure.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-07-31T14:31:12.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139098/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139098/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139098/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-15","Hotheifa Bader Khalifa","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel about the imprisonment of Hotheifa Bader Khalifa under an Administrative Detention order since May 2018.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL17183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139099","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-31","<p>We continue to have strong concerns about reports of ill-treatment of Palestinian minors in Israeli military detention, and regularly make representations to the Israeli authorities. Most recently, officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv raised our concerns with the Israeli Ministry of Justice on 6 June, and we continue to seek improvements to Israeli practices.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-07-31T13:56:10.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139099/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139099/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139099/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-15","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they intend to make to the government of Israel about the case of a 17 year old Palestinian who has been held in detention for one year without charge in Israel.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL17184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139100","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-31","<p>We continue to raise with our Israeli counterparts our concerns about the humanitarian and environmental impact of the damage to water sources and the destruction of Palestinian agricultural land that has been caused by the occupation, and settlement-related activity. Demolitions and evictions also jeopardise the viability of a future Palestinian state. We have repeatedly made clear to the Israeli authorities our serious concern at the increase in demolitions of Palestinian properties and call on them to cease the policy of demolitions and provide a clear, transparent route to construction for Palestinians.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-07-31T13:55:48.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139100/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139100/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139100/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-15","West Bank: Israel","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they intend to make to the government of Israel about reports that a Palestinian nature reserve, wells, and trees, have been destroyed by Israeli forces near Yatta in the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL17185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139101","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-31","<p>We are deeply concerned that demolitions and evictions of villages in the West Bank have a devastating impact on the communities concerned and will likely open the way for further settlement expansion – endangering the viability of the two-state solution. We have been clear about our grave concerns with the Israeli authorities and we regularly raise the matter through our Embassy in Tel Aviv.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-07-31T14:47:31.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139101/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139101/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139101/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-15","Israel: Bedouin","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they intend to take to prevent the Bedouin village of Um Al-Kheir in the South Hebron Hills being demolished by Israeli forces.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL17186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139102","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-31","<p>We are aware of reports about Mohammed Samir Obeid. While we have not raised the case, we will continue to monitor the situation. We urge all sides to treat the dead with respect and urge Israel to return any bodies they are holding.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-07-31T14:47:46.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139102/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139102/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139102/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-15","Mohammed Samir Obeid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they intend to make to the government of Israel about reports that it has not released the body of Mohammed Samir Obeid who was killed by Israeli forces.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL17187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139103","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-31","<p>We have repeatedly made clear to Israel our concerns about the use of live ammunition by the Israel Defense Forces in response to protests. In particular we have stressed the importance of protecting civilians, especially children and medical personnel. Palestinians have the right to protest peacefully. We have also been clear that Israel has the right to protect itself. While we recognise Israel's legitimate need to deploy security measures, we encourage them to deploy these in a way which minimises tension and use appropriate force. In instances where there have been accusations of excessive use of force, we have advocated swift, transparent investigations. We regularly raise our concerns with the Israeli authorities about their treatment of Palestinian minors.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-07-31T13:57:25.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139103/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139103/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139103/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-15","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they intend to make to the government of Israel about reports that a 10 year old Palestinian child was shot in the head during a peaceful procession in Kufur Qaddoum in the northern West Bank.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL17188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139104","Treasury","false","2019-07-19","<p>The government keeps public sector pensions policy under constant review in the context of the wider public finances.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Health and Social Care will shortly publish a consultation on proposals for a new flexibility for senior clinicians in the NHS pension scheme via the introduction of a 50:50 option.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2019-07-19T11:07:28.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139104/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139104/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139104/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-07-15","Public Sector: Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have, if any, to change the pension arrangements for senior public servants, especially doctors in the NHS, as they approach retirement.","false","Biography information for Lord Trefgarne",,"Lord Trefgarne","HL17189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139105","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-24","<p>The Government has not made an assessment of the risk to pedestrians on pavements of the wing mirrors on buses and other large vehicles, as this level of detail is not collected in road traffic collision information.</p><p> </p><p>Vehicle regulations are made at an international level and United Nations Economic Commission for Europe Regulation 46 already includes provisions to protect pedestrians with regard to the mirror of a moving vehicle.</p>",,"Baroness Vere of Norbiton",,"2019-07-24T12:01:12.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139105/answer","Biography information for Baroness Vere of Norbiton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139105/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1139105/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-15","Pedestrians: Safety","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the risk to pedestrians on pavements of the wing mirrors on buses and other large vehicles; and what steps they will take to ensure that pedestrians are not at risk of being struck by the wing mirrors of such vehicles.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL17190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138443","Department for Education","false","2019-07-16","<p>The most recent statistics on apprenticeships starts by industry sector cover the academic years 2012/13 to 2016/17 and are published on GOV.UK:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/apprenticeships-in-england-by-industry-characteristics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/apprenticeships-in-england-by-industry-characteristics</a>.</p><p>In 2016/17 there were:</p><ul><li>36,170 starts in the manufacturing sector;</li><li>1,620 starts in the energy sector; and</li><li>31,610 starts in the construction sector.</li></ul><p>Statistics for 2017/18 are due to be published in October 2019.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","276215 ; 276216","2019-07-16T11:38:48.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138443/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138443/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138443/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-12","Construction: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many apprenticeships were created in the construction sector in 2018.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","276218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138607","Department for Education","false","2019-07-17","<p>The process to become an academy is school led, with schools’ Local Governing Bodies taking the initiative to apply to their Regional School Commissioners’ office on whether to join an existing academy trust, or form one with partner schools. The only exception to this, where the department takes a leading role, is where a school is judged as ‘inadequate’ by Ofsted, as the law requires the Secretary of State to make an order enabling the school to become an academy.</p><p> </p><p>The department aims to ensure that all schools considering becoming academies are able to join strong academy trusts, and this has historically been supported through trust capacity funding. Ultimately, our ambition is for every school that wants to, to benefit from the autonomy and freedom to innovate that academy status offers, and for schools to collaborate through strong academy trusts.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-07-17T14:43:33.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138607/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138607/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138607/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-12","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent steps he has taken to help ensure that schools take the leading role in deciding whether to (a) form and (b) join a multi-academy trust.","false","Biography information for Eddie Hughes","Walsall North","Eddie Hughes","276587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138608","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-17","<p>​We regularly make representations on Mr <strong>Johal</strong>'s behalf, including raising his right to a fair trial. Our High Commissioner in India raised this with the Indian High Commissioner to the UK most recently on 10 June.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-07-17T14:41:27.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138608/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138608/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138608/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-12","Jagtar Singh Johal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Indian counterpart on the time taken to conduct the trial of Jagtar Singh Johal in that country.","false","Biography information for Eddie Hughes","Walsall North","Eddie Hughes","276588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138609","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-17","<p>The timescale for completing the national review of Care Treatment Review policy is by spring 2020.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-07-17T15:25:05.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138609/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138609/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138609/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-12","Autism and Learning Disability: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the NHS Long Term Plan Implementation Framework: system support offer, what his timescale is for completing the national review of Care Treatment Review policies.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","276531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138610","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-17","<p>All commissioners in England have a responsibility to assure themselves of the quality of the services that they commission. The Quality Assurance Framework and Commissioning for Quality Toolkit provide support and guidance for commissioners to undertake this appropriately, in line with their responsibilities. Annex A of the Long Term Plan for the National Health Service sets out the funding which has been allocated to support the commitments in the Long-Term Plan and the previous requirements from the Five Year Forward View, in addition to the published five-year clinical commissioning group allocations.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-07-17T15:16:45.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138610/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138610/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138610/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-12","Autism and Learning Disability: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the NHS Long Term Plan Implementation Framework: system support offer, whether the quality assurance framework to strengthen existing oversight arrangements for autistic people and people with learning disabilities will be mandatory; and what funding local authorities and CCGs will receive to ensure they can follow that framework.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","276532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138611","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-17","<p>NHS England has invested in better perinatal mental health care for new and expectant mothers, with at least 9,000 additional women receiving treatment last year. This represents significant progress against the target set out in the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health for at least 30,000 additional women each year to access evidence-based specialist perinatal mental health treatment by 2020/21.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS Long Term Plan includes a commitment for a further 24,000 women to be able to access specialist perinatal mental health care by 2023/24, building on the additional 30,000 women who will access these services each year by 2020/21. Specialist care will also be available from preconception to 24 months after birth, which will provide an extra year of support.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-07-17T15:54:22.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138611/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138611/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138611/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-12","Pregnancy: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the NHS Long Term Plan Implementation Framework, what targets his Department has set for increased access to specialist community perinatal mental health services in 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","276533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138612","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-17","<p>As set out in the NHS Long Term Plan, by 2023/24 at least an additional 345,000 children and young people aged 0-25 will be able to access support via National Health Service-funded mental health services and school or college-based mental health support teams.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-07-17T15:55:02.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138612/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138612/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-12","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the NHS Long Term Plan Implementation Framework, what the timeframe is for meeting the target of 345,000 additional children and young people being able to access NHS-funded mental health services.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","276534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138613","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-17","<p>The NHS Long Term Plan committed that investment in mental health services will grow faster than the National Health Service budget overall for each of the next five years, creating a new ringfenced local investment fund worth at least £2.3 billion a year by 2023/24. In addition, funding for children and young people’s mental health services, including mental health support teams, will grow faster than both overall NHS funding and total mental health spending.</p><p> </p><p>Funding allocations will be made to local areas in consultation with NHS England and NHS Improvement regions to support the development of school or college-based mental health support teams in all regions, additional to clinical commissioning group baseline funding.</p><p> </p><p>Details of the funding to be made available to individual systems will be decided through the five-year planning process.</p><p> </p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-07-17T15:55:28.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138613/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138613/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-12","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the NHS Long Term Plan Implementation Framework, how much additional funding he plans to allocate to support the development of school or college-based Mental Health Support Teams.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","276535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138614","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-07-17","<p>We are currently analysing the responses and evidence submitted to the consultation on introducing a deposit return scheme in England, Wales and Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-07-17T15:42:55.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138614/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138614/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138614/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-07-12","Plastics: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of a return scheme for plastic bottles of all sizes for the economy.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","276508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138615","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-17","<p>From 2015 up to the end of first quarter of 2019, HS2 Ltd received 1,224 Freedom of Information (FOI) and Environmental Information Regulations (EIR) requests. Where an exemption (FOI) or an exception (EIR) applied, all of the requested information was withheld on 239 occasions. The proportion of resolvable requests withheld in full for each period is as follows: (a) 2015, 12% (b) 2016, 19% (c) 2017, 25% (d) 2018, 19% and (e) first quarter of 2019, 24%.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2019-07-17T13:18:11.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138615/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138615/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-12","High Speed Two: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of freedom of information requests received by HS2 Limited were resolvable requests withheld in full for (a) 2015, (b) 2016, (c) 2017, (d) 2018 and (e) the first quarter of 2019.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","276515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138616","Department for Education","false","2019-07-22","<p>The Requirements for School Food Regulations (2014), which came into force in January 2015, regulates the food and drink provided at both lunchtime and at other times of the school day. Beyond this, we believe that headteachers, school governors and caterers are best placed to make decisions about their school food policies, taking into account local circumstances and the needs of their pupils. In doing so, we expect schools to make reasonable adjustments for pupils with particular requirements, for example to reflect dietary and cultural needs. School food policies work best when schools discuss them with parents and pupils, so that parents have the opportunity to raise pupils’ particular dietary needs.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-07-22T16:35:32.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138616/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138616/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-12","School Meals: Vegetarianism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what his policy is on encouraging schools to expand vegetarian options for school meals.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","276580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138617","Home Office","false","2019-07-17","<p>The Government intends to legislate to establish a requirement for the police and the Independent Office for Police Conduct (IOPC) to provide written notification to the Local Policing Body and, as appropriate, other prescribed parties, when an investigation into alleged police misconduct takes more than 12 months to complete.</p><p>A further notification will be required every 6 months thereafter if necessary. The notification will require the police or IOPC to provide an update on the progress of the investigation, an estimate of when it expects the report of the investigation to be submitted, an explanation for any delay and a summary of planned steps to bring the investigation to a conclusion.</p><p>This is the first time that the police or IOPC will have a statutory requirement to report on timeliness of investigations. This increased level of scrutiny is intended to improve accountability, and greater transparency will help to deliver further improvements in timeliness.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","276578 ; 276579","2019-07-17T15:45:38.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138617/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138617/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-12","Police: Disciplinary Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 25 June 2019 to Question 267262 on Police: Disciplinary Proceedings, what information a written explanation is required to include in the event of an investigation going beyond 12 months.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","276577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138618","Home Office","false","2019-07-17","<p>The Government intends to legislate to establish a requirement for the police and the Independent Office for Police Conduct (IOPC) to provide written notification to the Local Policing Body and, as appropriate, other prescribed parties, when an investigation into alleged police misconduct takes more than 12 months to complete.</p><p>A further notification will be required every 6 months thereafter if necessary. The notification will require the police or IOPC to provide an update on the progress of the investigation, an estimate of when it expects the report of the investigation to be submitted, an explanation for any delay and a summary of planned steps to bring the investigation to a conclusion.</p><p>This is the first time that the police or IOPC will have a statutory requirement to report on timeliness of investigations. This increased level of scrutiny is intended to improve accountability, and greater transparency will help to deliver further improvements in timeliness.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","276577 ; 276579","2019-07-17T15:45:38.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138618/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138618/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-12","Police: Disciplinary Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 25 June 2019 to Question 267262 on Police: Disciplinary Proceedings, what plans he has to ensure the (a) police and (b) Independent Office for Police Conduct take forward the next steps identified in the event of an investigation going beyond 12 months.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","276578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138619","Home Office","false","2019-07-17","<p>The Government intends to legislate to establish a requirement for the police and the Independent Office for Police Conduct (IOPC) to provide written notification to the Local Policing Body and, as appropriate, other prescribed parties, when an investigation into alleged police misconduct takes more than 12 months to complete.</p><p>A further notification will be required every 6 months thereafter if necessary. The notification will require the police or IOPC to provide an update on the progress of the investigation, an estimate of when it expects the report of the investigation to be submitted, an explanation for any delay and a summary of planned steps to bring the investigation to a conclusion.</p><p>This is the first time that the police or IOPC will have a statutory requirement to report on timeliness of investigations. This increased level of scrutiny is intended to improve accountability, and greater transparency will help to deliver further improvements in timeliness.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","276577 ; 276578","2019-07-17T15:45:38.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138619/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138619/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138619/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-12","Police: Disciplinary Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 25 June 2019 to Question 267262 on Police: Disciplinary Proceedings, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of requiring a written explanation in the event of an investigation going beyond 12 months times on lowering investigation times; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","276579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138620","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-22","<p>​The UK remains deeply concerned by the situation in Libya. We are actively engaged in international diplomatic efforts to secure an end to the fighting and a return to the UN-led political process. As penholder on Libya in the UN Security Council, we agreed a Security Council statement on 6 July condemning the abhorrent attack on the Tajoura migrant detention centre, in which so many lost their lives. The UK, US, France, Italy, Egypt and the United Arab Emirates agreed a statement on 16 July, supporting the mediation efforts of UN Envoy Ghassan Salame and calling for a halt to the fighting and return to UN-led political talks. There can be no military solution in Libya; only an inclusive political settlement will bring about the stability its citizens deserve.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","276559","2019-07-22T14:43:35.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138620/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138620/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-12","Libya: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent steps the Government has taken to work towards finding a political solution to the conflict in Libya.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","276558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138621","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-22","<p>​The UK remains deeply concerned by the situation in Libya. We are actively engaged in international diplomatic efforts to secure an end to the fighting and a return to the UN-led political process. As penholder on Libya in the UN Security Council, we agreed a Security Council statement on 6 July condemning the abhorrent attack on the Tajoura migrant detention centre, in which so many lost their lives. The UK, US, France, Italy, Egypt and the United Arab Emirates agreed a statement on 16 July, supporting the mediation efforts of UN Envoy Ghassan Salame and calling for a halt to the fighting and return to UN-led political talks. There can be no military solution in Libya; only an inclusive political settlement will bring about the stability its citizens deserve.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","276558","2019-07-22T14:43:35.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138621/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138621/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-12","Libya: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his international counterparts on the assault on the UN-backed Government of National Accord in Libya.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","276559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138622","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-22","<p>​The UK condemns the abhorrent attack on the detention centre in Tajoura and supports the UN Secretary-General's call for an investigation. We are clear that the full facts of this attack must be established and, ultimately, those responsible for violations of International Humanitarian Law must be held to account. This tragic incident underlines the need for all parties to de-escalate, allow humanitarian access, and return to UN political mediation.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-07-22T14:45:07.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138622/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138622/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-12","Libya: Detention Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will support calls for a UN Investigation into the recent airstrike on a migrant detention centre in Tripoli.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","276560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138623","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-22","<p>​We are concerned by reports of military equipment entering Libya from a range of sources. We take all such reports seriously, given the UN arms embargo. On 16 July the UK agreed a P3+3 statement (by the UK, US, France, Italy, Egypt and the United Arab Emirates), calling on all UN member states to fully respect their obligations under the relevant UN Security Council resolutions to contribute to Libya's peace and stability and to prevent destabilising arms shipments to Libya.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-07-22T14:46:06.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138623/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138623/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-12","Libya: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his French counterpart on arms sales to combatants in the conflict in Libya.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","276561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138624","Home Office","false","2019-07-16","<p>Fire and rescue services have the resources they need to do their important work and will receive around £2.3 billion in 2019/20.</p><p>Fire and Rescue Services funding requirements from 2020/21 will be considered as part of the Spending Review.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2019-07-16T16:02:37.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138624/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138624/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-12","Fire and Rescue Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if he will allocate more funding to the fire service in the 2019-20 financial year.","false","Biography information for Faisal Rashid","Warrington South","Faisal Rashid","276608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138625","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-17","<p>When I met with First Deputy Foreign Minister Vladimir Titov in February, I made clear that Russia must address the concerns of the international community, including ending their destabilising activity in Ukraine. Our position is clear that Russia needs to end its financial and military support for armed separatists and fully respect Ukraine's independence and territorial integrity. We will continue to be one of the strongest supporters of Ukrainian defence and security.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2019-07-17T16:19:46.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138625/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138625/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-12","Russia: Ukraine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Russian counterpart on the role the Russian military in Ukraine.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","276524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138626","Department for International Trade","false","2019-07-17","<p>The Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria provide a thorough risk assessment framework for considering licence applications, and take into account the respect for human rights and fundamental freedoms in the country of final destination.</p><p> </p><p>Licensing decisions are based on the most up-to-date information and analysis available at the time, including reports from NGOs and our overseas network.</p><p> </p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2019-07-17T11:36:26.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138626/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138626/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-07-12","Surveillance: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to comply with the recommendation of the UN Special Rapporteur on freedom of opinion and expression to impose an immediate moratorium on the export, sale, transfer, use or servicing of privately developed surveillance tools until a human rights-compliant safeguards regime is in place.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","276582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138627","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-17","<p>The British Government has regular discussions with Ukraine, including at Ministerial level, on Russia's aggression against Ukraine and continued threats to Ukrainian sovereignty. Our position is clear that Russia must end its financial and military support for armed separatists and fully respect Ukraine's independence and territorial integrity. We will continue to be one of the strongest supporters of Ukrainian defence and security. Since 2015 the UK has helped build the resilience and capacity of the Ukrainian Armed Forces through Operation Orbital, providing training to over 16,000 personnel so far. HMS Duncan visited Odessa on 7 July as part of Exercise Sea Breeze and hosted Ukrainian President Zelenskyy on board the ship.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2019-07-17T16:22:13.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138627/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138627/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-12","Russia: Ukraine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Ukrainian counterpart on the involvement of the Russian military in Ukraine.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","276525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138628","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-17","<p>The UK continues to encourage and support Sri Lanka to deliver the commitments it made to the UN Human Rights Council (UNHRC) through Resolutions 30/1, 34/1 and 40/1. We firmly believe that this is the best framework for establishing truth and achieving justice and lasting reconciliation. The Government has made these points regularly to Sri Lankan Ministers, including during a Ministerial visit to Colombo in October and in a number of meetings since. The British High Commissioner in Colombo also holds regular discussions on the implementation of the UNHRC resolutions with the Government of Sri Lanka.</p><p>In March the UK welcomed the Annual Report of the Office of the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights, which assessed progress made by the Sri Lankan Government in the implementation of UNHRC resolutions 30/1 and 34/1. The Report found that the Government of Sri Lanka had taken some steps to address human rights concerns and to introduce more democratic and accountable government, including the return of some military-held civilian land, the establishment of an Office of Missing Persons and the ratification of the Convention on Enforced Disappearances.</p><p>However, more needs to be done. The UK has urged further progress on these issues, and encouraged the Government of Sri Lanka to deliver meaningful devolution through constitutional reform, and to establish and then utilise credible mechanisms for transitional justice. We continue to urge the Government to prioritise the steps required to deliver fully on the commitments it made in resolutions 30/1, 34/1 and 40/1, and to develop a comprehensive and time bound implementation strategy.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-07-17T14:39:37.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138628/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138628/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-12","Sri Lanka: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Sri Lankan counterpart on the implementation of UN Human Rights Council resolutions regarding the aftermath of the Sri Lankan civil war.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","276526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138629","Department for International Trade","false","2019-07-17","<p>The Government publishes Official Statistics (on a quarterly and annual basis) about export licences granted, refused and revoked on GOV.UK. These reports contain detailed information by destination, including the overall value, type (e.g. Military, Other) and a summary of the items covered by these licences. These can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/strategic-export-controls-licensing-data." target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/strategic-export-controls-licensing-data.</a></p><p>The data currently provides details of licences up to 31 March 2019. Information about the period 1 April to 30 June will be published in October 2019 and data covering the period 1 July 2019 to 30 September 2019 will be published in January 2020.</p><p>All export licences are issued in strict accordance with the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2019-07-17T11:43:38.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138629/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138629/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-07-12","Surveillance: Philippines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether the UK exported surveillance equipment to the Philippines in 2019.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","276583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138630","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-07-22","<p>The reforms to the Social Fund in 2013 allowed local authorities in England and the devolved administrations in Scotland and Wales to deliver their own local provision for people who are in need of urgent help. Local authorities are best placed to decide how to promote and target flexible help to support local welfare needs. The Government has no further plans to review provision.</p><p> </p><p>The Local Government Finance Settlement for 2015-16 identifies a notional amount relating to local welfare provision in each upper-tier and unitary authority’s general grant, totalling £129.6 million for England. The notional allocation for local welfare provision remains at £129.6 million in England in the Local Government Financial Settlement until 2019/20. There are no plans to ring-fence this notional allocation.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","276565 ; 276576","2019-07-22T15:11:48.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138630/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138630/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-07-12","Welfare Assistance Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps her Department is taking to (a) promote and (b) fund local welfare assistance.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","276564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138631","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-07-22","<p>The reforms to the Social Fund in 2013 allowed local authorities in England and the devolved administrations in Scotland and Wales to deliver their own local provision for people who are in need of urgent help. Local authorities are best placed to decide how to promote and target flexible help to support local welfare needs. The Government has no further plans to review provision.</p><p> </p><p>The Local Government Finance Settlement for 2015-16 identifies a notional amount relating to local welfare provision in each upper-tier and unitary authority’s general grant, totalling £129.6 million for England. The notional allocation for local welfare provision remains at £129.6 million in England in the Local Government Financial Settlement until 2019/20. There are no plans to ring-fence this notional allocation.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","276564 ; 276576","2019-07-22T15:11:48.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138631/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138631/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-07-12","Welfare Assistance Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will allocate additional funding for local welfare assistance.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","276565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138632","Treasury","false","2019-07-19","<p>The Government keeps public sector pay and pensions policy under constant review in the context of the wider public finances. The same tax rules must apply identically to everyone in the same situation, regardless of their employer.</p><p> </p><p>Pensions tax relief is one of the most expensive reliefs in the personal tax system. In 2017/18 income tax and employer National Insurance Contributions relief cost over £50 billion, with around two-thirds going to higher and additional rate taxpayers.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has listened carefully to specific concerns raised by some high-earning NHS consultants impacted by annual allowance tax charges.</p><p> </p><p>In response, the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care has announced his intention to consult on proposals for a new 50:50 option providing pension flexibility for senior clinicians in the NHS. This flexibility will give senior clinicians in England and Wales more choice in respect of their pension accrual, and therefore the ability to control better any pensions tax charges.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2019-07-19T12:03:41.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138632/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138632/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-07-12","Hospitals: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of  change the level of tax for NHS consultants working overtime.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","276566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138633","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-18","<p>No patient data is being shared with Amazon as part of this agreement. The collaboration with Amazon simply connects people to medical information that is already freely available through the National Health Service website. Use of Amazon Alexa is just an alternative mechanism for accessing that information.</p><p>The agreement signed between the Department and Amazon is clear that none of the data generated through voice search using Alexa will be shared with third parties; that it will not be used for selling products or making product recommendations to Amazon users; nor is it building any form of health profiles on Amazon customers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-07-18T15:33:33.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138633/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138633/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-12","NHS: Amazon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the Government's announcement that NHS health information will be made available through Amazon’s Alexa, what steps he plans to take to ensure the privacy of patient data.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","276567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138634","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-18","<p>Reducing elective care waiting times continues to be a high priority for the National Health Service. The NHS Long Term Plan sets out the NHS priorities and reiterates the focus on increasing the amount of planned surgery year-on-year, to cut long waits, and reduce the size of hospital waiting lists.</p><p> </p><p>The Long Term Plan also reinforces the NHS commitment to offer choice, including the promise of choice at 26 weeks. This will be delivered as a full rollout over the next year of the planned NHS-managed choice process, which will systematically identify 26-week waiters and contact them to offer choice for treatment at an earlier date.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2019-07-18T15:48:35.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138634/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138634/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-12","Surgery: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking reduce waiting times for routine operations.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","276568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138635","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-17","<p>The Government has not made representations to the US Administration in relation to this specific case. The British Government's long-standing position remains that the detention facility at Guantanamo Bay should close.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2019-07-17T16:13:16.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138635/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138635/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-12","Abdullatif Nasser","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether his Department has made representations to the US Administration for the release of Abdullatif Nasser after Mr Nasser was cleared for transfer in 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","276505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138636","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-17","<p>The British Government's long-standing position remains that the detention facility at Guantanamo Bay should close and we continue to engage with the US Government on this issue to make this position clear. The UK continues to work closely with the US on a wide range of national security issues.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2019-07-17T16:16:58.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138636/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138636/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-12","Guantanamo Bay: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has made to the US Administration on releasing Guantanamo Bay inmates who have been cleared for release by the Periodic Review Board.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","276506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138639","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-17","<p>No one should have to face long waits for an autism assessment. We expect services to adhere to the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) quality standard which recommends that the length between referral and a first appointment to start an assessment should be no more than three months.</p><p>We are determined to drive up performance nationally. We will use data on autism diagnosis waiting times, available for the first time later this year, to hold local areas to account and act where waiting times exceed the NICE standard.</p><p>Whilst a diagnosis of autism should happen as soon as possible, it is important to recognise that a diagnosis is often complex and can involve different professionals and agencies. We are following the prevailing clinical guidance set out by NICE.</p><p>NHS England and NHS Improvement encourage local areas to follow existing NICE guidelines and quality standards when commissioning and delivering diagnosis services for both children and adults.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","276606 ; 276607","2019-07-17T15:23:52.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138639/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138639/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-12","Autism: Diagnosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will take steps to reduce waiting times for autism assessments for adults.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","276605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138640","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-17","<p>No one should have to face long waits for an autism assessment. We expect services to adhere to the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) quality standard which recommends that the length between referral and a first appointment to start an assessment should be no more than three months.</p><p>We are determined to drive up performance nationally. We will use data on autism diagnosis waiting times, available for the first time later this year, to hold local areas to account and act where waiting times exceed the NICE standard.</p><p>Whilst a diagnosis of autism should happen as soon as possible, it is important to recognise that a diagnosis is often complex and can involve different professionals and agencies. We are following the prevailing clinical guidance set out by NICE.</p><p>NHS England and NHS Improvement encourage local areas to follow existing NICE guidelines and quality standards when commissioning and delivering diagnosis services for both children and adults.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","276605 ; 276607","2019-07-17T15:23:52.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138640/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138640/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-12","Autism: Diagnosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will take steps with NHS England to implement a waiting time standard for autism diagnosis in the CCG Improvement and Assessment Framework in order to tackle regional differences.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","276606"
