"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138461","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-17","<p>MHCLG is not aware of any cases where the cladding on a building has needed to be remediated on more than one occasion since June 2017.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-07-17T15:38:25.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138461/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138461/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138461/answer","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138461/answer/previousversion/129432","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-11","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department is aware of buildings for which cladding has needed to be remediated on more than one occasion since June 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","276196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138462","Department for International Development","false","2019-07-16","<p>The UK is clear that no health workers or aid workers should be at risk of violence, that they must have the protection they need from the responsible authorities to allow them to do their jobs in safety, and that the rule of law must prevail to deal with perpetrators.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-07-16T15:53:03.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138462/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138462/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138462/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-07-11","Occupied Territories: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps he is taking to help ensure that (a) health workers in the Occupied Palestinian Territories are protected from attack and (b) perpetrators of such attacks are held accountable.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","276132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138463","Department for International Development","false","2019-07-16","<p>Restrictions on movement and access imposed by the Israeli authorities on Gaza have resulted in a worsening of the already poor humanitarian situation. In May, 2,206 permit applications were made to the Government of Israel to enter Israel at the Erez crossing for healthcare, with 61% approved, 8% denied and 31% delayed. In the same month, 2,426 patient companion applications were made with 47% approved, 13% denied and 40% pending. The UK regularly raises and will continue to call on the Israeli government to ease access restrictions further and for Israel and the Palestinian Authority to work together to ensure a durable solution for Gaza. In addition to our diplomatic efforts, we have recently announced a new £1.6 million package of support to be delivered through the World Health Organisation which will help to provide life-saving treatment to more than 380,000 people in Gaza, including a new limb unit.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-07-16T16:50:28.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138463/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138463/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138463/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-07-11","Gaza: Patients","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment his Department has made of the effect of permit restrictions imposed by the Government of Israel on (a) medical patients and (b) companions of those medical patients seeking to exit Gaza.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","276133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138464","Department for International Trade","false","2019-07-16","<p>We do not propose to place documents related to these court proceedings in the Library. There are specific rules of court procedure concerning access to documents on the court file in line with principles of open justice which provide a mechanism for public access.</p><p> </p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2019-07-16T09:32:07.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138464/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138464/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138464/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-07-11","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will place in the Library a copy of the witness statement of the Head of the Export Control Joint Unit dated 27 June 2019 in his Department's application to appeal the Court of Appeal judgment of 20 June 2019.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","276268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138465","Cabinet Office","false","2019-07-16","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to my answer given to Question 271623 on 2 July 2019.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2019-07-16T14:07:56.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138465/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138465/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138465/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-07-11","GovTech Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 11 July 2019 to Question 274634, what cost/benefit analyses have been conducted for each of the catalyst challenges; and if he will publish those analyses.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","276283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138466","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-07-16","<p>We will update the House at the appropriate time.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2019-07-16T15:42:05.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138466/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138466/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138466/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-07-11","Government Departments: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 10 of the Government Transformation Strategy, how many of the 10 commitments the Government intended to complete before 2020 are on track to be completed.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","276284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138467","Department for Education","false","2019-07-16","<p>The Department welcomes the National Literacy Trust’s research on reading in both print and digital forms.</p><p>The Department wants children to develop the habit of reading widely and often, for both pleasure and information, whatever the format. Research suggests that reading for pleasure is more important for children’s educational development than their parents’ level of education.</p><p>There is sound evidence that systematic synthetic phonics is a highly effective method of teaching reading to children. Phonics performance is improving: in 2018, there were 163,000 more 6-year-olds on track to become fluent readers compared to 2012. This represented 82% of pupils meeting the expected standard in the phonics screening check, compared to just 58% when the check was introduced in 2012.</p><p>Building on the success of our phonics partnerships and phonics roadshows programmes, in 2018, the Department launched a £26.3 million English Hubs Programme. Hub schools are taking a leading role in improving the teaching of early reading through systematic synthetic phonics, early language development, and reading for pleasure. The Department has appointed 34 primary schools across England as English Hubs.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-07-16T16:46:41.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138467/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138467/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138467/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-11","Literacy: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the National Literacy Trust's report Children, young people and digital reading, published by the  on 30 April 2019, on the literacy benefits of children reading both digital and print formats.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","276252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138468","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-16","<p>From 2015 up to the end of first quarter of 2019, HS2 Ltd responded to 79 per cent of the Freedom of Information (FOI) and Environmental Information Regulations (EIR) requests it received within the 20 working day deadline.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of requests</p></td><td><p>% of FOI received fulfilled within the 20-day deadline</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>226</p></td><td><p>77%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>219</p></td><td><p>95%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>284</p></td><td><p>92%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p>354</p></td><td><p>77%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>In the first quarter of 2019 HS2 Ltd has received 141 FOI request with 40% fulfilled within the 20-day deadline. This is an increase of 83 per cent in the number of requests received, coupled with an increase in complexity, this has led to a number of requests taking longer to process. HS2 Ltd recognises that its performance needs to improve. It is implementing a number of measures, including increasing resources, to alleviate the issue.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","276158","2019-07-16T15:21:45.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138468/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138468/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138468/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-11","High Speed Two: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what percentage of freedom of information requests received by HS2 Limited were fulfilled within the 20-day deadline in (a) 2015, (b) 2016, (c) 2017, (d) 2018 and (e) the first quarter of 2019.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","276157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138469","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-16","<p>From 2015 up to the end of first quarter of 2019, HS2 Ltd responded to 79 per cent of the Freedom of Information (FOI) and Environmental Information Regulations (EIR) requests it received within the 20 working day deadline.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of requests</p></td><td><p>% of FOI received fulfilled within the 20-day deadline</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>226</p></td><td><p>77%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>219</p></td><td><p>95%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>284</p></td><td><p>92%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p>354</p></td><td><p>77%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>In the first quarter of 2019 HS2 Ltd has received 141 FOI request with 40% fulfilled within the 20-day deadline. This is an increase of 83 per cent in the number of requests received, coupled with an increase in complexity, this has led to a number of requests taking longer to process. HS2 Ltd recognises that its performance needs to improve. It is implementing a number of measures, including increasing resources, to alleviate the issue.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","276157","2019-07-16T15:21:44.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138469/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138469/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138469/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-11","High Speed Two: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many freedom of information requests were received by HS2 Limited in (a) 2015, (b) 2016, (c) 2017, (d) 2018 and (e) the first quarter of 2019.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","276158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138470","Home Office","false","2019-07-16","<p>When an offer of compensation is made the Home Office will write to the claimant setting out the reasons for that decision.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-07-16T12:31:17.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138470/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138470/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138470/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-11","Immigration: Windrush Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether people applying to the Windrush compensation scheme who request a Tier 1 or Tier 2 review will have access to the evidence or data upon which an initial or review decision has been made.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","276276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138471","Home Office","false","2019-07-16","<p>The immigration exemption in the Data Protection Act 2018 is not a blanket exemption and may only be used on a case by case basis where the prejudice test and the proportionality test have been applied. It is not targeted at any individual cohort or schemes.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-07-16T12:42:33.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138471/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138471/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138471/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-11","Immigration: Windrush Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether people applying to the Windrush compensation scheme will be subject to the immigration exemption to the Data Protection Act 2018.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","276277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138472","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-16","<p>Central government funding for Newcastle City Council and other English local authorities in 2020/21 will be subject to the planned Spending Review and confirmed through the 2020-21 Local Government Finance Settlement.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2019-07-16T16:25:15.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138472/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138472/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138472/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-11","Local Government Finance: Newcastle upon Tyne","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what central Government funding Newcastle Local Authority will be allocated for its 2020-21 budget.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","276189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138473","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-17","<p>Government intervention to provide funding for the removal of unsafe Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding is wholly exceptional. It is based on the unparalleled risk ACM poses, very real public safety concerns and the failure of many building owners to do the right thing by their residents.</p><p>Government intervention does not remove responsibility for overall building safety from the building owner and if fire safety risks are uncovered, they must remedy them, or potentially face enforcement action from the local authority. We have made it clear that building owners should protect leaseholders from bearing the costs of remediation, and that the clearest way to ensure safety is to remove unsafe materials.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-07-17T15:36:53.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138473/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138473/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138473/answer","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138473/answer/previousversion/129429","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-11","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, for what reasons his Department is not providing funds for the remediation of non-Aluminium composite cladding where it is found to be unsafe.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","276197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138474","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-07-16","<p>In accordance with the Freedom of Information Act 2000 (the Act) the 20 working day deadline for response to requests for information may be extended in order to consider the balance of public interest regarding disclosure of held information.</p><p>In 2018, 82% of requests received by the Department were answered within the statutory 20-day deadline or with a permitted extension. In the first quarter of 2019, 68% of requests were answered within the 20-day deadline or with a permitted extension.</p><p>The complexity and diverse nature of the Department means that individual requests may require the involvement of more than one area of the Department and/or consultation with key stakeholders. Regrettably this can sometimes lead to delays in the Department’s ability to providing a timely response.</p><p>The Department remains committed to improving the number of requests answered within the statutory deadline and is working closely with officials across the Department.</p>","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","276160","2019-07-16T14:42:41.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138474/answer","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138474/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138474/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-07-11","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, for what reasons 31.2 per cent of freedom of information requests received by his Department were not fulfilled within the 20-day deadline in 2018.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","276159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138475","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-07-16","<p>In accordance with the Freedom of Information Act 2000 (the Act) the 20 working day deadline for response to requests for information may be extended in order to consider the balance of public interest regarding disclosure of held information.</p><p>In 2018, 82% of requests received by the Department were answered within the statutory 20-day deadline or with a permitted extension. In the first quarter of 2019, 68% of requests were answered within the 20-day deadline or with a permitted extension.</p><p>The complexity and diverse nature of the Department means that individual requests may require the involvement of more than one area of the Department and/or consultation with key stakeholders. Regrettably this can sometimes lead to delays in the Department’s ability to providing a timely response.</p><p>The Department remains committed to improving the number of requests answered within the statutory deadline and is working closely with officials across the Department.</p>","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","276159","2019-07-16T14:42:41.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138475/answer","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138475/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138475/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-07-11","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, for what reason only 55.4 per cent of FOI requests received by his Department in the first quarter of 2019 were met within the 20-day deadline.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","276160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138476","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-17","<p>The Department has not issued specific advice to local authorities on the remediation of High Pressure Laminate cladding (HPL).</p><p>The Department has published guidance to reiterate the importance of building owners assessing their buildings and ensuring that non-Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding systems are safe. Advice Note 14, published in 2017 and updated in December 2018, reiterates that the clearest way to ensure safety is to remove unsafe materials. This can be found at:<strong> <a href="https://gbr01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fassets.publishing.service.gov.uk%2Fgovernment%2Fuploads%2Fsystem%2Fuploads%2Fattachment_data%2Ffile%2F765761%2FExpert_Panel_advice_note_on_non-ACM.pdf&amp;data=02%7C01%7CBalraj.Phull%40communities.gov.uk%7C822baa5e0f8045ab0d3e08d708fcefd7%7Cbf3468109c7d43dea87224a2ef3995a8%7C0%7C0%7C636987754750895449&amp;sdata=B0ihsM3pe6VxZrRQaSStWhwRjyZ%2F1SGucZlDXihbf%2FI%3D&amp;reserved=0" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/765761/Expert_Panel_advice_note_on_non-ACM.pdf</a></strong></p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-07-17T15:40:05.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138476/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138476/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138476/answer","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138476/answer/previousversion/129428","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-11","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference the article in the Oxford Mail entitled, Hockmore Tower among five Oxford blocks facing post Grenfell scrutiny, published 11 July 2019, what information his Department has provided to local authorities in July 2019 on the need to remediate high-pressure laminate cladding.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","276198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138477","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-17","<p>Members of the National Fire Chiefs Council and the Independent Expert Advisory Panel were invited.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-07-17T15:40:31.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138477/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138477/answer","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138477/answer/previousversion/129427","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-11","Buildings: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether the National Fire Chiefs Council or his Department's Independent Expert Panel have been invited to witness the large-scale fire safety tests commissioned by his Department in July 2019.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","276199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138478","Home Office","false","2019-07-16","<p>The Home Office does not intend to keep up a running commentary on payments made. We will publish information on the number of claims submitted, number of claims paid and the overall amount paid out by the scheme in due course as part of our regular reporting to HASC.</p><p>The criteria used to calculate loss of income are set out in the scheme rules available on gov.uk</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-07-16T12:36:29.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138478/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138478/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-11","Immigration: Windrush Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Windrush compensation scheme, what the average offer has been to an applicant and what criteria his Department uses to calculate loss of income in such awards.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","276278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138479","Department for Education","false","2019-07-16","<p>My right hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Education, has had many discussions with the Chancellor about a range of issues across the department. Spending plans beyond 2019-20 will be set at the next Spending Review and we cannot pre-empt these decisions. The department is committed to securing the right deal for early years education.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-07-16T10:22:56.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138479/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138479/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-11","Pre-school Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor for the Exchequer on increasing funding for early years education in the forthcoming spending review.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","276255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138480","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-16","<p>The Anti-Muslim Hatred Working Group was established to consider and take forward proposals to tackle anti-Muslim hatred. Members are expected to interact regularly with a broad range stakeholders at an individual and organisational level. This includes Muslim communities, key partners, government departments, local service providers, police and interfaith groups.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-07-16T11:47:37.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138480/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138480/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-11","Anti-muslim Hatred Working Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, which (a) persons and (b) organisations the Anti-Muslim Hatred Working Group has met with in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","276245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138481","Department for Education","false","2019-07-16","<p>All future funding decisions on our early education entitlements will be taken as part of the forthcoming Spending Review.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-07-16T10:48:24.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138481/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138481/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-11","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will maintain Government funding for the 30-hours childcare policy.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","276256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138482","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-16","<p>The terms of reference of the Anti-Muslim Hatred Working Group were last reviewed during the process to refresh the membership this year. The terms of reference are reviewed regularly.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-07-16T11:47:57.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138482/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138482/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-11","Anti-muslim Hatred Working Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, when the terms of reference of the Anti-Muslim Hatred Working Group (a) were last and (b) are next due to be reviewed.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","276246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138483","Home Office","false","2019-07-17","<p>The Treasury has agreed that payments made under the Windrush Compensation Scheme and the Windrush Urgent and Exceptional Payments Scheme will be disregarded on an extra-statutory basis in the calculation of Universal Credit and other DWP means-tested benefits.</p><p>Similarly, payments under, or in connection with, the Windrush Compensation scheme will be disregarded in full for 52 weeks from the date the payment is made when calculating for tax credit awards.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-07-17T15:34:36.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138483/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138483/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-11","Immigration: Windrush Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether compensation awarded from the Windrush compensation scheme is taken into account in an assessment for an application for (a) universal credit, (b) tax credits and (c) other benefits.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","276279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138484","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-18","<p>The Anti-Muslim Hatred Working Group meets quarterly. Independent members of the Working Group work alongside the listed departments, representatives from the Muslim communities, independent experts, academics, and ex-officio members of the Working Group to tackle anti-Muslim hatred.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-07-18T13:03:56.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138484/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138484/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-07-11","Anti-Muslim Hatred Working Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what engagement the Anti-Muslim Hatred Working Group has had with the (a) Attorney General’s Office, (b) Cabinet Office, (c) Crown Prosecution Service, (d) Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, (e) Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government, (f) Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport; (g) Department for Education, (h) Foreign and Commonwealth Office, (i) Home Office, (j) Ministry of Justice, and (k) Department for Transport in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","276247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138485","Department for Education","false","2019-07-16","<p>We want parents to have access to a range of affordable childcare, giving them increased flexibility in their working hours and helping children thrive in the crucial early years. That is why the Department for Education is investing £3.5 billion in early education offers this year alone, more than any previous government.</p><p>The ‘Steps to Sustainability’ report makes a valuable contribution to our knowledge base about early education and childcare. We continue to monitor the provider market closely through a range of projects which provide insight into various aspects of the provider market.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-07-16T10:52:56.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138485/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138485/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-11","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the APPG for Childcare and Early Education July 2019 report entitled Steps to Sustainability; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","276257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138486","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-19","<p>Ahead of a potential exit on 29 March, DfT worked with a number of Departments to develop planning assumptions for a potential no deal exit. Since April, Departments have reviewed the planning assumptions and developed new assumptions based on the most recent information from Member States and in light of the extension to 31 October 2019. These assumptions are focused on a reasonable worst case scenario, rather than what we expect to happen, and have already been shared with key partners to support revision of contingency plans, where appropriate, for a potential no deal scenario on 31 October. These planning assumptions remain under review throughout the planning process. The Government does not publish sensitive risk assessments of this nature.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2019-07-19T13:05:39.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138486/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138486/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-11","Channel Ferries: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 12 June 2019 to Question 259958 on Channel Ferries: Freight, if he publish the existing planning assumptions; and when he plans to announce a decision on a revision of those assumptions.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","276181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138487","Department for Education","false","2019-07-16","<p>The information requested is not held centrally. The department’s annual childcare and early years provider survey provides an estimate on the size of the early years’ workforce. Based on the 2018 survey findings, there are an estimated 430,500 staff working in early years provision (including staff in school nurseries and reception classes). This information is available at the following link: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/788753/Survey_of_Childcare_and_Early_Years_Providers_2018_Main_Summary.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/788753/Survey_of_Childcare_and_Early_Years_Providers_2018_Main_Summary.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-07-16T11:08:23.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138487/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138487/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-11","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of levels of (a) recruitment and (b) retention in the childcare sector in the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","276258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138488","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-19","<p>Following the extension to Article 50, Government Ministers and their Officials have reviewed and developed new border planning assumptions based on the most recent information available. These assumptions are focused on a reasonable worst case scenario, rather than what we expect to happen, and have already been shared with key partners to support contingency planning, where appropriate, should the UK leave the European Union on 31 October without a deal.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2019-07-19T11:15:53.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138488/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138488/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-11","Channel Ferries: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 12 June 2019 to Question 259958 on Channel Ferries: Freight, which (a) Ministers and (b) officials in his Department are working on the existing planning assumptions; and what deadline he has set for revised assumptions to be reported to him.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","276182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138489","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-19","<p>The Department continues to liaise closely with the Port of Dover with regard to contingency and resilience measures that could be applied in the event of a no deal exit from the European Union. This includes plans to ensure that England’s roads are ready for EU exit, including operations to manage both passenger and freight traffic using the port in the event of disruption. The Port itself continues to engage closely with Government on no deal preparations. With regard to managing any impact on seafarers serving Dover routes, the responsibility sits with the relevant shipping companies or employers in the first instance.</p><p> </p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2019-07-19T11:35:16.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138489/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138489/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-11","Dover Port","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what contingency preparations he is making at the Port of Dover for (a) passengers, (b) hauliers and (c) seafarers in the event that the UK leaves the EU on 31 October 2019 without a deal.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","276183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138490","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-19","<p>The number of people working on EU Exit within the Department, including staff working on preparations at major ports for the UK leaving the EU on 31 October without a deal, can change in accordance with priorities. Therefore, it is not possible to provide a breakdown of staff numbers due to staff working on a variety of areas relating to EU Exit in parallel with each other.</p><p> </p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2019-07-19T11:07:02.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138490/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138490/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-11","Ports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff in his Department are working on preparations at major ports for the UK leaving the EU on 31 October 2019 without a deal.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","276184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138491","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-16","<p>No such assessment has been made. The Government keeps evidence on tobacco control under review. Decisions on the best licensed smoking cessation support to prescribe are a matter for clinicians in discussion with their patients, taking account of guidance including advice published by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-07-16T14:34:30.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138491/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138491/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-11","Smoking: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of implications for his policies of the recent study published in the journal, Nicotine & Tobacco Research entitled, Prescribing prevalence, effectiveness, and mental health safety of smoking cessation medicines in patients with mental disorders.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","276169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138492","Department for Education","false","2019-07-16","<p>Ofsted publishes termly data on childcare providers and inspections. This statistical release confirms the number of providers that have registered with Ofsted (joiners) and the number that have left (leavers) in the relevant period. No data is published on trends of childcare settings opening and closing in affluent areas compared to disadvantaged areas.</p><p>As at 31 March 2019, there were 76,600 childcare providers registered with Ofsted, down by 1% (600) since December 2018. However, the overall number of childcare places increased by 3,200 since December 2018. This information is available at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/childcare-providers-and-inspections-as-at-31-march-2019/childcare-providers-and-inspections-as-at-31-march-2019-main-findings" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/childcare-providers-and-inspections-as-at-31-march-2019/childcare-providers-and-inspections-as-at-31-march-2019-main-findings</a>.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-07-16T11:21:05.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138492/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138492/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-11","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of trends in the level of the (a) opening and (b) closure of childcare settings in (a) affluent and (b) disadvantaged areas.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","276259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138493","Department for Education","false","2019-07-19","<p>In total the government has spent £18.4 million on the consultation, preparation and introduction of the National Assessment and Accreditation System (NAAS) for child and family social workers.</p><p>These costs can be further broken down into:</p><ul><li>£4.6 million in preparation costs, which includes money spent on the proof of concept phase, the preparation of assessment materials and standard setting;</li><li>£4.1 million up to June 2018 on the introduction of assessments, of this £3.5 million has been in grants made to local authorities to support Children’s Services Departments and individual social workers prepare for the assessment;</li><li>£3.7 million from July 2018 to May 2019 was spent on running assessment centres and paid to private consultants to deliver this service; and</li><li>a further £6 million in 2018-19, which has been in grants to local authorities.</li></ul><p>The department has spent no funds on consultation. The consultation and programme development of the NAAS has been resourced directly by the civil service who have engaged widely with both local authorities and individual social workers.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","276203","2019-07-19T14:00:55.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138493/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138493/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138493/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-11","Department for Education: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department has spent on the (a) consultation on, (b) preparation for and (c) introduction of the National Assessment and Accreditation Systems for (i) social workers, (ii) social work supervisors and (iii) leaders.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","276201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138494","Department for Education","false","2019-07-16","<p>The Partners in Practice programme includes one Community Interest Company (Achieving for Children) and one independent Trust (Doncaster Children’s Services Trust). No funding has been provided from the Partners in Practice programme to assist with the setting up of these arrangements.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-07-16T16:21:18.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138494/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138494/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-11","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what financial support Partners in Practice has provided to each local authority to help establish (a) Trust models and (b) Community Interest Companies in relation to local authority children's services departments.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","276202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138495","Department for Education","false","2019-07-19","<p>In total the government has spent £18.4 million on the consultation, preparation and introduction of the National Assessment and Accreditation System (NAAS) for child and family social workers.</p><p>These costs can be further broken down into:</p><ul><li>£4.6 million in preparation costs, which includes money spent on the proof of concept phase, the preparation of assessment materials and standard setting;</li><li>£4.1 million up to June 2018 on the introduction of assessments, of this £3.5 million has been in grants made to local authorities to support Children’s Services Departments and individual social workers prepare for the assessment;</li><li>£3.7 million from July 2018 to May 2019 was spent on running assessment centres and paid to private consultants to deliver this service; and</li><li>a further £6 million in 2018-19, which has been in grants to local authorities.</li></ul><p>The department has spent no funds on consultation. The consultation and programme development of the NAAS has been resourced directly by the civil service who have engaged widely with both local authorities and individual social workers.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","276201","2019-07-19T14:00:55.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138495/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138495/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-11","Social Services: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of funding allocated to the consultation on the National Assessment and Accreditation System for social workers was spent on (a) private sector consultants and (b) local authorities in 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","276203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138496","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-09-02","<p>We will update the House at the appropriate time.</p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams",,"2019-09-02T11:11:17.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138496/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138496/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-07-11","Government Chief Data Officer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what role the government Chief Data Officer will have in the implementation of the National Data Strategy.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","276285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138497","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-07-16","<p>The Strategy, which will be titled The UK's Defence Contribution in the High North, will be published shortly.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2019-07-16T15:25:21.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138497/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138497/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138497/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-07-11","Arctic: Defence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when she plans to publish the Defence Arctic Strategy.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","276171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138498","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-07-16","<p>The Ministry of Defence is firmly committed to a number of space programmes, and we are continually assessing our space capabilities, coherence and requirements. Our strategic work on space has developed significantly and will play a key role in Spending Review decisions. We expect to publish later this year.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2019-07-16T16:39:54.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138498/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138498/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1138498/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-07-11","Defence: Space Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when she plans to publish the Defence Space Strategy.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","276172"
